The 4 Steps of Manual Compilation
1.
Write Code (.java files)

What it is: You write your program's logic in human-readable files with a .java extension.

Why: This is the source and the blueprint for your application.

2. Gather Dependencies (.jar files)
Your code imports Lanterna, so you must provide that library. You did this by downloading its JAR file.

Example: The Lanterna library file.

Path: my-app/lib/lanterna-3.1.1.jar

Command to get it:
Shell Script
# This command downloads the JAR into your 'lib' folder.
wget -P my-app/lib https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/com/googlecode/lanterna/lanterna/3.1.1/lanterna-3.1.1.jar

3. Compile (javac command)
You translate your human-readable .java files into machine-readable .class files.

Command:
Shell Script
javac -d my-app/bin -cp "my-app/lib/lanterna-3.1.1.jar" my-app/src/main/java/*.java

Explanation:

javac: The compiler.

-d my-app/bin: "Place the compiled .class files into the my-app/bin directory."

-cp "my-app/lib/lanterna-3.1.1.jar": "While compiling, look inside this JAR file to find the Lanterna code you imported."

my-app/src/main/java/*.java: "Compile every .java file in the source directory."

4. Run (java command)
You execute the compiled code to start your game.

Command:
Shell Script
java -cp "my-app/bin:my-app/lib/lanterna-3.1.1.jar" main

Explanation:

java: The Java runtime.

-cp "my-app/bin:my-app/lib/lanterna-3.1.1.jar": "To run this program, find the necessary classes in two places:
    a. my-app/bin (for your own compiled code like main.class, Player.class, etc.)
    b. my-app/lib/lanterna-3.1.1.jar (for the library code)."

main: "The name of the class to start with (e.g., main.class becomes main)."